; v0.3 Track B: the scoped `clock` capability executes across backends.
;
; `stamp` reads `clock.now` (a deterministic monotonic tick, 0 on the first read)
; without a capability scope, so the effect gate rejects it with
; CAPABILITY_NOT_IN_SCOPE. The loop wraps the read in `(with (clock) …)` and
; re-checks — the same convergence as `log-scope`, on a different scoped
; capability. Because `clock.now` is deterministic (not wall-clock) and each
; oracle check runs a fresh interpreter, `stamp(a)` is `a + 0` = `a`, so the
; oracle is stable and byte-identical across interp/native/wasm.
(module clockstamp
  (fn stamp (params (a i64)) (ret i64)
    (body (call i64.add (ref a) (call clock.now)))))
